 =20

We   talked yesterday about Bed Bath & Beyond Inc.=E2=80=99s unusual rescue=
 financing deal. Bed Bath was, apparently, a whisker away from filing for a=
 messy bankruptcy, and was instead saved by a huge equity investment   led =
by Hudson Bay Capital Management. The investors  paid Bed Bath $225 million=
 for some convertible preferred stock and warrants, and promised to put up =
another $800 million for more convertible preferred stock if things go well=
.=C2=A0
I suggested yesterday that the best way to understand this deal is not that=
 Hudson Bay and friends are long-term equity investors in Bed Bath, but tha=
t they are planning to buy stock from Bed Bath at a substantial discount to=
 the market price, and then turn around and sell it into the market. The in=
vestors paid Bed Bath about $225 million for $237 million face amount of co=
nvertible preferred stock (that is, they got a 5% discount): Today,=C2=A0th=
at $237=C2=A0million of convertible preferred stock is convertible into com=
mon stock at  a conversion price of=C2=A0$2.3727. That means that the inves=
tors could convert one $10,000 preferred share =E2=80=94=C2=A0that they bou=
ght for $9,500 =E2=80=94=C2=A0into 4,214.6 shares of common stock. The stoc=
k closed yesterday at $3.01; it was trading at about $2.58 at noon today. T=
he investors could sell their 4,214.6 shares today for about $10,873, for a=
 $1,373 profit on their $9,500 investment, a 14% return in, you know, a day=
.
The conversion price will vary over time, but it will always be at least 8%=
 lower than the market price of the stock, with a floor of $0.716 and a cap=
 of, I think, something like $3.16.
  [1]
=C2=A0So unless the stock falls below $0.716, Hudson Bay will always be abl=
e to convert its preferred, a little at a time, to get cheap shares and sel=
l them at a profit. And Bed Bath can demand that Hudson Bay put up $800 mil=
lion more to buy more preferred, also a little at a time, but only if the s=
tock is trading above about $1.25, to leave some cushion for it to sell sto=
ck profitably.
There are various constraints on this, the main one being that Bed Bath=E2=
=80=99s entire market capitalization is about $300 million, and Hudson Bay =
et al. will have about a billion dollars=E2=80=99 worth of stock to sell. T=
hey=E2=80=99re not dumping it all this afternoon. But, relatively speaking,=
 Bed Bath is a pretty attractive stock to do this in. It trades a lot =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0the average volume of the stock in 2023 so far has been about 9=
4 million shares per day =E2=80=94=C2=A0and it has occasional meme-driven p=
rice spikes that Hudson Bay et al. can sell into. Also it was a heavily=C2=
=A0shorted=C2=A0stock, as lots of investors were sensibly betting that it w=
as about to go bankrupt and the stock would go to zero; this creates both g=
ood meme-stock vibes and also a source of demand for the stock. (Short sell=
ers, seeing the company rescued from bankruptcy, might want to cover their =
shorts by buying the stock from Hudson Bay.)
Also Hudson Bay has incentives to, as it were, manage the stock price well.=
 If it dumps as much as it can as fast as it can, it might push the stock b=
elow $0.716 and start to lose money. If it sells slowly and the stock recov=
ers, it has enormous upside: Its conversion price is capped at something li=
ke $3.16, so if the stock gets to $5 it will have huge profits on every con=
version. Also it owns millions of warrants to buy more shares at $6.15. Hud=
son Bay does not have a ton of downside exposure to the stock =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0it makes a profit as long as the stock is above $0.716 =E2=80=94=C2=A0bu=
t it does have a ton of upside.
There are other ways to make money on this position: If you were a Bed Bath=
=C2=A0bondholder, and you bought the bonds at around 5 cents on the dollar =
last month, participating in this rescue would have given you a quick profi=
t on your bond position, since the bonds traded up to as much as 25 cents o=
n the dollar after Bed Bath averted bankruptcy. And meme stocks tend to hav=
e active options markets: The investors in this deal effectively bought=C2=
=A0options=C2=A0to buy Bed Bath stock at very cheap prices, and could presu=
mably make money by turning around and selling similar options at higher pr=
ices.
  [2]

But I do think that the simplest explanation is that Hudson Bay has committ=
ed to paying Bed Bath roughly $1 billion, over the course of the next year,=
 and in exchange Bed Bath will give Hudson Bay stock that it can sell into =
the market, over time, for considerably more than $1 billion. In a sense Be=
d Bath could do this itself, and avoid paying Hudson Bay a huge expected pr=
ofit for acting as a middleman, but:
=09Hudson Bay thought of it and Bed Bath didn=E2=80=99t! Worth something.=
=09It is awkward for a company to try to dump $1 billion of stock directly =
on retail shareholders while it is close to bankruptcy; having Hudson Bay a=
s a middleman gives a bit more distance.=09Bed Bath is, over time, frequent=
ly going to have material nonpublic information that would prevent it from =
selling stock. Hudson Bay=E2=80=99s involvement solves that problem: Hudson=
 Bay won=E2=80=99t have any material nonpublic information, and each time i=
t exercises some preferred stock it will get shares that it can sell immedi=
ately.=C2=A0

Incidentally, I say =E2=80=9CHudson Bay.=E2=80=9D It is not public how much=
 of the deal went to Hudson Bay and how much went to other investors, but t=
here are some hints. One is that the $800 million=C2=A0future=C2=A0commitme=
nt =E2=80=94=C2=A0the =E2=80=9Cpreferred stock warrants=E2=80=9D allowing, =
and also requiring, investors to buy more of the convertible preferred stoc=
k over the next year =E2=80=94=C2=A0is  divided pro rata among =E2=80=9Cinv=
estors that purchase $75,000,000 or more=E2=80=9D of the initial deal. That=
 is one-third of the initial deal, meaning that an absolute maximum of thre=
e investors could be on the hook for the future commitments. But only Hudso=
n Bay has been reported as an =E2=80=9Canchor investor=E2=80=9D in the deal=
, which presumably means that it is much bigger than any other investor. If=
 Hudson Bay is in for $100 million of the initial deal, and no one else is =
in for more than $50 million, then that means that Hudson Bay is going to d=
o the entire remaining $800 million. I am not sure that is what is happenin=
g, but it seems logical.
One other point on that.=C2=A0Bed Bath is listed on the Nasdaq, and Nasdaq =
has a rule saying that listed companies need to get shareholder approval be=
fore issuing more than 20% of their stock.
  [3]
=C2=A0The idea is that if a company wants to sell a big chunk of its stock =
to a single investor, or a handful of investors, then its existing sharehol=
ders should get a say in the matter: You don=E2=80=99t want the company to =
be able to give someone else=C2=A0control=C2=A0of its stock without consult=
ing shareholders. This rule applies to selling common stock, but also to se=
lling stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0like Bed Bath=E2=80=99s convertible preferred =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0that can convert into common stock.
There are exceptions, though. One is=C2=A0that if you sell stock at the mar=
ket price,
  [4]
then you don=E2=80=99t need a shareholder vote; the idea is that you are no=
t giving anyone a sweetheart deal if they are just buying at market prices.
The other is that if you do a =E2=80=9Cpublic offering,=E2=80=9D then you d=
on=E2=80=99t need to consult shareholders. Again the intuition is that if y=
ou do a public stock offering, you are not giving anyone a sweetheart deal;=
 anyone can participate in the offering so no one is getting favored.
What about this deal? Well, Bed Bath has about 117 million shares of common=
 stock outstanding, so 20% of that would be about 23 million shares. The co=
nvertible preferred stock that it issued yesterday will convert into roughl=
y 100 million shares of common stock (85% of the current share count), plus=
 there are warrants for another 95 million (81%), plus Bed Bath plans to is=
sue another $800 million shares of convertible preferred that would convert=
 into hundreds of millions more shares of common stock. The ultimate plan i=
s to issue as many as 780 million shares of common stock in the Hudson Bay =
deal, or about 667% of its currently outstanding stock.
  [5]
=C2=A0So, more than 20%.
As for the price, the convertible preferred is initially convertible into c=
ommon stock at $2.3727 per share. The stock closed at $3.01 yesterday, $5.8=
6 the day before, and no lower than $2.82 last week. So, Hudson Bay definit=
ely gets stock at a discount.
But is it a public offering? Well, sure, sort of; it was a publicly registe=
red offering, underwritten by an investment bank (B. Riley Securities). The=
 Nasdaq rules say that =E2=80=9CGenerally, a firm commitment underwritten s=
ecurities offering registered with the Securities and Exchange Commission w=
ill be considered a public offering for these purposes,=E2=80=9D though the=
y leave some wiggle room. =E2=80=9CWhen determining whether an offering is =
a =E2=80=98public offering=E2=80=99 for purposes of these rules, Nasdaq sta=
ff will consider all relevant factors,=E2=80=9D the rules add, including =
=E2=80=9Cthe manner in which the offering is marketed (including the number=
 of investors offered securities, how those investors were chosen, and the =
breadth of the marketing effort)=E2=80=9D as well as =E2=80=9Cthe extent of=
 the offering's distribution (including the number and identity of the inve=
stors who participate in the offering and whether any prior relationship ex=
isted between the Company and those investors).=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Again I don=E2=80=99t know how much Hudson Bay got of the deal, or how wide=
ly it was marketed. It is certainly a=C2=A0weird=C2=A0deal, publicly market=
ed over one day (yesterday) by a specialty investment bank; I am not sure h=
ow many public investors were able to do the work and put orders into the d=
eal, or whether Bed Bath really wanted them to. In some technical sense thi=
s was a broad public offering, but it seems like it was really a bespoke de=
al for a handful of investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0or one investor =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0who knew exactly what they wanted and got it.=C2=A0

