I wrote once  about the crime dial:
In general, the chief compliance officer at any company has a dial in front=
 of her that she can turn to get More Crime or Less Crime, and at a normal =
company =E2=80=94 a bank, for instance =E2=80=94 her job consists of (1) tu=
rning it most of the way toward Less Crime, but (2) not all the way, and (3=
) acting very contrite when politicians and regulators yell at her about th=
e residual crime. =E2=80=9CWe have a zero-tolerance policy for crime,=E2=80=
=9D she will say, and almost mean.
Now, in practice, every day, a bank=E2=80=99s compliance officer will face =
the choice of (1) leaving the dial alone, (2) turning it a touch toward Mor=
e Crime or (3) turning it a touch toward Less Crime. Presumably most days s=
he will mostly leave it alone and focus on other things. Some days, she wil=
l adjust it a scooch one way or the other, in ways that don=E2=80=99t reall=
y get noticed much outside of the bank. Occasionally the dial will have dri=
fted too far toward More Crime, the bank will have a huge scandal, she will=
 be fired, and her successor will make a big show of cranking the dial a lo=
ng way toward Less Crime. =E2=80=9CWe had too much crime,=E2=80=9D the new =
compliance officer will say, =E2=80=9Cbut from now on we will have a zero-t=
olerance policy toward crime.=E2=80=9D This still won=E2=80=99t be true, bu=
t it will (1) still almost be true and (2) be a bit more true than it was b=
efore the scandal.
This problem is not wholly symmetrical: It is rarer for the bank to run int=
o huge problems because the dial has drifted too far toward Less Crime, and=
 to then make a big show of cranking the dial a long way toward More Crime.=
 =E2=80=9CWe had too little crime,=E2=80=9D a bank=E2=80=99s compliance off=
icer will pretty much never say, =E2=80=9Cbut from now on we will have a mu=
ch more tolerant policy toward crime.=E2=80=9D
Still! The problem is a little=C2=A0symmetrical.=C2=A0One way to ensure tha=
t you never do any illegal business is to never do any business,
  [6]
 and that probably goes too far. Sometimes you do have to  crank the dial b=
ack:

Credit Suisse Group AG, fighting to stem a wave of investor outflows, is di=
aling back some stringent anti-money laundering controls in Asia after they=
 drew protests from clients and bankers and contributed to staff departures=
.=C2=A0
A requirement that private bankers verify most of their clients=E2=80=99 so=
urces of wealth was eased near the end of last year, while third-party tran=
sactions are no longer subject to executive approvals, according to people =
familiar with the matter.=C2=A0
The backtracking highlights the delicate balance facing the bank as it trie=
s to tighten operations following a series of scandals, while hanging on to=
 clients in one of the fastest-growing regions for money management. The me=
asures, more stringent than at many peers, threatened to stall efforts to r=
ecover from massive outflows that contributed to another quarterly loss for=
 the embattled bank.

One funny part of this story is that, after Credit Suisse had various scand=
als, it =E2=80=9Ctook steps in 2021 to tighten controls by commissioning Er=
nst & Young to assess its wealth units=E2=80=99 anti-money laundering proce=
dures in Singapore and Hong Kong.=E2=80=9D If you are an outside auditor br=
ought in to do a report on anti-money laundering procedures, the problem is=
 not symmetrical at all,=C2=A0for you. If you recommend =E2=80=9Ca robust =
=E2=80=98belt and braces=E2=80=99 approach=E2=80=9D (as a Credit Suisse spo=
kesperson called it in a statement to Bloomberg News), and the approach is=
=C2=A0so=C2=A0robust that the clients can never get business approved and t=
he bankers all quit, that=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0your=C2=A0problem; you were hi=
red to stop money laundering, and you did. You bring in an outside consulta=
nt, you=E2=80=99re gonna get the dial cranked way too far over toward Less =
Crime. And then you have to nudge it back.

