      NFT Stuff
   =20
 =20

One thing that you can do is make a handbag that looks like an Herm=C3=A8s =
Birkin bag, call it a =E2=80=9CBirkin bag,=E2=80=9D and sell it to people f=
or money. The problems with this are:
=09Hard to make the bag, you need materials and labor and stuff, you=E2=80=
=99ve got to ship it to customers, etc.; and=09You are definitely violating=
 Herm=C3=A8s=E2=80=99s trademark and they=E2=80=99ll sue you and win.

Another thing you can do is draw a picture on your computer that looks like=
 an Herm=C3=A8s Birkin bag, call it (the picture) a =E2=80=9CMetaBirkin bag=
,=E2=80=9D and sell it to people for money. The advantages of this are:
=09Pretty easy to draw a picture on your computer, and your shipping costs =
(of emailing people the picture) are negligible.=09If Herm=C3=A8s sues you,=
 you can do a dumb little dance and say =E2=80=9Cwhat, no, I=E2=80=99m not=
=C2=A0copying=C2=A0your=C2=A0Birkin bag, I am making a sly and subtle joke =
about value and consumption and late capitalism.=E2=80=9D

You might naively think that people would=C2=A0pay less money=C2=A0for a co=
mputer picture of a handbag than they would for an actual handbag, but in t=
he early 2020s there was a brief bizarre bubble in non-fungible tokens, and=
 for a while people would pay=C2=A0more=C2=A0for a computer picture of a th=
ing than for the actual thing. There were some good jokes to be made about =
value and consumption and late capitalism, but Herm=C3=A8s was not really t=
he problem.
Anyway this happened,=C2=A0Herm=C3=A8s did sue the MetaBirkin guy, we talke=
d about it the other day, and today Herm=C3=A8s won:

Luxury brand Herm=C3=A8s International SA won its lawsuit against the digit=
al artist behind =E2=80=9CMetaBirkin=E2=80=9D nonfungible tokens after conv=
incing a Manhattan federal jury that Mason Rothschild=E2=80=99s sale of the=
 NFTs violated Herm=C3=A8s=E2=80=99 rights to the =E2=80=9CBirkin=E2=80=9D =
trademark.
The nine-person jury returned a verdict on Wednesday, awarding Herm=C3=A8s =
$133,000 in total damages. They also found Rothschild=E2=80=99s NFTs aren=
=E2=80=99t protected speech under the First Amendment. ...
The 100 MetaBirkin NFTs are linked to digital images depicting Herm=C3=A8s=
=E2=80=99 iconic Birkin luxury handbag, but covered in colorful, cartoonish=
 fur instead of leather. Rothschild created and sold the NFTs in late 2021 =
after an extensive marketing campaign through his social media and website.
The jury determined that the NFTs are more akin to consumer products subjec=
t to strict trademark laws that protect brands from copycats and those look=
ing to capitalize on their goodwill.
Throughout the case, Rothschild argued that his NFTs are works of art prote=
cted by the First Amendment, no different from Andy Warhol=E2=80=99s famous=
 silk-screen prints of Campbell=E2=80=99s soup cans. His attorneys characte=
rized the NFT project as an =E2=80=9Cartistic experiment=E2=80=9D that exam=
ined how society places value on status symbols.
Physical Birkin bags range in price from $12,000 to close to $200,000. Roth=
schild first sold the NFTs for around $450 each, but their resale value roc=
keted to tens of thousands of dollars.
A blockchain expert testified during trial that Rothschild made around 55.2=
 Ethereum tokens, worth about $87,700 today.

Look, do you know what is a good =E2=80=9Cartistic experiment that examines=
 how society places value on status symbols=E2=80=9D?=C2=A0Herm=C3=A8s. Her=
m=C3=A8s is running a constant sophisticated experiment in how society plac=
es value on status symbols: It produces=C2=A0status symbols, tries to price=
 them to extract maximum value, tries to balance=C2=A0exclusivity against m=
aximizing revenue, etc. You don=E2=80=99t need some computer guy to come al=
ong and be like =E2=80=9Cooooh ooooh ooooh these handbags sell at a premium=
 to their cost of production, what is society even doing,=C2=A0ooooh,=C2=A0=
ooooh.=E2=80=9D Herm=C3=A8s does that! That=E2=80=99s Herm=C3=A8s=E2=80=99s=
 whole business!=C2=A0They=E2=80=99re=C2=A0not confused about what they=E2=
=80=99re doing! The people who buy Birkin bags aren=E2=80=99t confused abou=
t what they=E2=80=99re doing! Rothschild didn=E2=80=99t need to clarify or =
examine it! Herm=C3=A8s is doing it fine!
Obviously Rothschild=E2=80=99s experiment instead examined how society plac=
ed value on computer images that imitate Birkin bags, and for a while the a=
nswer was =E2=80=9Csociety values those pictures a lot because they are som=
ehow status symbols.=E2=80=9D In some sense anyone who does any scam is run=
ning an artistic experiment that examines how much money people are willing=
 to give them, but that is not a defense!
I guess the next step is to seize the MetaBirkins and shred them? In the me=
taverse or whatever? And take a video of the shredding and sell that as an =
NFT? Man what an embarrassing time the NFT boom was.

