<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bed Bath &amp; cetera</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/30494731.273449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDcvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLXNvbGQtc29tZS1zdG9jaz9jbXBp=
ZD1CQkQwMjA4MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2x=
ldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAyMDgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBbfc063ce" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked yesterday</a> about Bed Bath &amp; B=
eyond Inc.=E2=80=99s unusual rescue financing deal. Bed Bath was, apparentl=
y, a whisker away from filing for a messy bankruptcy, and was instead saved=
 by a huge equity investment <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/30494731.273449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDcvaHVkc29uLWJheS1jYXBpdGFsLXNhaWQtdG8tYW5jaG9yLWJlZC1iYXR=
oLWJleW9uZC1zaGFyZS1zYWxlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMDgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW=
09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIwOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ=
249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb7335be3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  led by Hudso=
n Bay Capital Management</a>. The investors <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/30494731.273449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoa=
XZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzg4NjE1OC8wMDAxMTkzMTI1MjMwMjcxMTcvZDQ1NTE3M2RleDk5Mi5o=
dG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB65a5e7a9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> paid Bed Bath $225 million<=
/a> for some convertible preferred stock and warrants, and promised to put =
up another $800 million for more convertible preferred stock if things go w=
ell.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suggested yesterday that the best way to und=
erstand this deal is not that Hudson Bay and friends are long-term equity i=
nvestors in Bed Bath, but that they are planning to buy stock from Bed Bath=
 at a substantial discount to the market price, and then turn around and se=
ll it into the market. The investors paid Bed Bath about $225 million for $=
237 million face amount of convertible preferred stock (that is, they got a=
 5% discount): Today,=C2=A0that $237=C2=A0million of convertible preferred =
stock is convertible into common stock at <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/30494731.273449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZ=
lcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzg4NjE1OC8wMDAxMTkzMTI1MjMwMjY2MzAvZDQwNjM2OGRmd3AuaHRt/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBae9f861b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a conversion price of=C2=A0$2.37=
27</a>. That means that the investors could convert one $10,000 preferred s=
hare =E2=80=94=C2=A0that they bought for $9,500 =E2=80=94=C2=A0into 4,214.6=
 shares of common stock. The stock closed yesterday at $3.01; it was tradin=
g at about $2.58 at noon today. The investors could sell their 4,214.6 shar=
es today for about $10,873, for a $1,373 profit on their $9,500 investment,=
 a 14% return in, you know, a day.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The conversion price will vary over time, but =
it will always be at least 8% lower than the market price of the stock, wit=
h a floor of $0.716 and a cap of, I think, something like $3.16.<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0So unless the stock falls below $0.716, Hudson Bay will always be=
 able to convert its preferred, a little at a time, to get cheap shares and=
 sell them at a profit. And Bed Bath can demand that Hudson Bay put up $800=
 million more to buy more preferred, also a little at a time, but only if t=
he stock is trading above about $1.25, to leave some cushion for it to sell=
 stock profitably.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are various constraints on this, the mai=
n one being that Bed Bath=E2=80=99s entire market capitalization is about $=
300 million, and Hudson Bay et al. will have about a billion dollars=E2=80=
=99 worth of stock to sell. They=E2=80=99re not dumping it all this afterno=
on. But, relatively speaking, Bed Bath is a pretty attractive stock to do t=
his in. It trades a lot =E2=80=94=C2=A0the average volume of the stock in 2=
023 so far has been about 94 million shares per day =E2=80=94=C2=A0and it h=
as occasional meme-driven price spikes that Hudson Bay et al. can sell into=
. Also it was a heavily=C2=A0<em>shorted=C2=A0</em>stock, as lots of invest=
ors were sensibly betting that it was about to go bankrupt and the stock wo=
uld go to zero; this creates both good meme-stock vibes and also a source o=
f demand for the stock. (Short sellers, seeing the company rescued from ban=
kruptcy, might want to cover their shorts by buying the stock from Hudson B=
ay.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also Hudson Bay has incentives to, as it were,=
 manage the stock price well. If it dumps as much as it can as fast as it c=
an, it might push the stock below $0.716 and start to lose money. If it sel=
ls slowly and the stock recovers, it has enormous upside: Its conversion pr=
ice is capped at something like $3.16, so if the stock gets to $5 it will h=
ave huge profits on every conversion. Also it owns millions of warrants to =
buy more shares at $6.15. Hudson Bay does not have a ton of downside exposu=
re to the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0it makes a profit as long as the stock is ab=
ove $0.716 =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it does have a ton of upside.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are other ways to make money on this pos=
ition: If you were a Bed Bath=C2=A0<em>bondholder</em>, and you bought the =
bonds at around 5 cents on the dollar last month, participating in this res=
cue would have given you a quick profit on your bond position, since the bo=
nds traded up to as much as 25 cents on the dollar after Bed Bath averted b=
ankruptcy. And meme stocks tend to have active options markets: The investo=
rs in this deal effectively bought=C2=A0<em>options=C2=A0</em>to buy Bed Ba=
th stock at very cheap prices, and could presumably make money by turning a=
round and selling similar options at higher prices.<a class=3D"footnote-ind=
ex" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displ=
ay: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I do think that the simplest explanation i=
s that Hudson Bay has committed to paying Bed Bath roughly $1 billion, over=
 the course of the next year, and in exchange Bed Bath will give Hudson Bay=
 stock that it can sell into the market, over time, for considerably more t=
han $1 billion. In a sense Bed Bath could do this itself, and avoid paying =
Hudson Bay a huge expected profit for acting as a middleman, but:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Hudson Bay thought of it and Bed Bath=
 didn=E2=80=99t! Worth something.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
It is awkward for a company to try to dump $1 billion of stock directly on =
retail shareholders while it is close to bankruptcy; having Hudson Bay as a=
 middleman gives a bit more distance.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">Bed Bath is, over time, frequently going to have material nonpublic inf=
ormation that would prevent it from selling stock. Hudson Bay=E2=80=99s inv=
olvement solves that problem: Hudson Bay won=E2=80=99t have any material no=
npublic information, and each time it exercises some preferred stock it wil=
l get shares that it can sell immediately.=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally, I say =E2=80=9CHudson Bay.=E2=80=
=9D It is not public how much of the deal went to Hudson Bay and how much w=
ent to other investors, but there are some hints. One is that the $800 mill=
ion=C2=A0<em>future=C2=A0</em>commitment =E2=80=94=C2=A0the =E2=80=9Cprefer=
red stock warrants=E2=80=9D allowing, and also requiring, investors to buy =
more of the convertible preferred stock over the next year =E2=80=94=C2=A0i=
s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30494731.273449/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzg4NjE1OC8wMDAxMTkzMTI=
1MjMwMjU3NjIvZDQwNjM2OGQ0MjRiNS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB70c4f900" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> divided pro rata</a> among =E2=80=9Cinvestors that purchase $75,000,0=
00 or more=E2=80=9D of the initial deal. That is one-third of the initial d=
eal, meaning that an absolute maximum of three investors could be on the ho=
ok for the future commitments. But only Hudson Bay has been reported as an =
=E2=80=9Canchor investor=E2=80=9D in the deal, which presumably means that =
it is much bigger than any other investor. If Hudson Bay is in for $100 mil=
lion of the initial deal, and no one else is in for more than $50 million, =
then that means that Hudson Bay is going to do the entire remaining $800 mi=
llion. I am not sure that is what is happening, but it seems logical.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One other point on that.=C2=A0Bed Bath is list=
ed on the Nasdaq, and Nasdaq has a rule saying that listed companies need t=
o get shareholder approval before issuing more than 20% of their stock.<a c=
lass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpare=
nt !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The idea is that if a company wants to sell a big chunk of its st=
ock to a single investor, or a handful of investors, then its existing shar=
eholders should get a say in the matter: You don=E2=80=99t want the company=
 to be able to give someone else=C2=A0<em>control=C2=A0</em>of its stock wi=
thout consulting shareholders. This rule applies to selling common stock, b=
ut also to selling stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0like Bed Bath=E2=80=99s convertible=
 preferred =E2=80=94=C2=A0that can convert into common stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are exceptions, though. One is=C2=A0that=
 if you sell stock at the market price,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"=
#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: n=
one !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-b=
lock;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>then you don=E2=80=99t need a shareholder vote; the idea is that you ar=
e not giving anyone a sweetheart deal if they are just buying at market pri=
ces.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other is that if you do a =E2=80=9Cpublic =
offering,=E2=80=9D then you don=E2=80=99t need to consult shareholders. Aga=
in the intuition is that if you do a public stock offering, you are not giv=
ing anyone a sweetheart deal; anyone can participate in the offering so no =
one is getting favored.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What about this deal? Well, Bed Bath has about=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30494731.273449/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvODg2MTU4LzAw=
MDA4ODYxNTgyMzAwMDAyNi9iYmJ5LTIwMjIxMTI2Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcba=
c700e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">117 million shares</a> of common stock outstanding, so 20% o=
f that would be about 23 million shares. The convertible preferred stock th=
at it issued yesterday will convert into roughly 100 million shares of comm=
on stock (85% of the current share count), plus there are warrants for anot=
her 95 million (81%), plus Bed Bath plans to issue another $800 million sha=
res of convertible preferred that would convert into hundreds of millions m=
ore shares of common stock. The ultimate plan is to issue as many as 780 mi=
llion shares of common stock in the Hudson Bay deal, or about 667% of its c=
urrently outstanding stock.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0So, more than 20%.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As for the price, the convertible preferred is=
 initially convertible into common stock at $2.3727 per share. The stock cl=
osed at $3.01 yesterday, $5.86 the day before, and no lower than $2.82 last=
 week. So, Hudson Bay definitely gets stock at a discount.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But is it a public offering? Well, sure, sort =
of; it was a publicly registered offering, underwritten by an investment ba=
nk (B. Riley Securities). The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/30494731.273449/aHR0cHM6Ly9saXN0aW5nY2VudGVyLm5hc2RhcS5jb20vcnV=
sZWJvb2svbmFzZGFxL3J1bGVzL05hc2RhcSUyMDU2MDAlMjBTZXJpZXM/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB76c82289" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">Nasdaq rules</a> say that =E2=80=9CGenerally, a fi=
rm commitment underwritten securities offering registered with the Securiti=
es and Exchange Commission will be considered a public offering for these p=
urposes,=E2=80=9D though they leave some wiggle room. =E2=80=9CWhen determi=
ning whether an offering is a =E2=80=98public offering=E2=80=99 for purpose=
s of these rules, Nasdaq staff will consider all relevant factors,=E2=80=9D=
 the rules add, including =E2=80=9Cthe manner in which the offering is mark=
eted (including the number of investors offered securities, how those inves=
tors were chosen, and the breadth of the marketing effort)=E2=80=9D as well=
 as =E2=80=9Cthe extent of the offering's distribution (including the numbe=
r and identity of the investors who participate in the offering and whether=
 any prior relationship existed between the Company and those investors).=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again I don=E2=80=99t know how much Hudson Bay=
 got of the deal, or how widely it was marketed. It is certainly a=C2=A0<em=
>weird=C2=A0</em>deal, publicly marketed over one day (yesterday) by a spec=
ialty investment bank; I am not sure how many public investors were able to=
 do the work and put orders into the deal, or whether Bed Bath really wante=
d them to. In some technical sense this was a broad public offering, but it=
 seems like it was really a bespoke deal for a handful of investors =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0or one investor =E2=80=94=C2=A0who knew exactly what they wanted a=
nd got it.=C2=A0</p>
