<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">People are worried about stock buybacks</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One reason to worry about stock buybacks is th=
at you think companies should never return money to shareholders. As far as=
 I can tell this is a real thing that some people believe, though I do not =
really understand it myself. My model of corporate finance is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">people give money to a company,</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">the company does stuff with the money =
to try to earn a profit, and=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>the company returns some of the profits to the people who gave it the mone=
y.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you didn=E2=80=99t have Step 3 then the who=
le thing wouldn=E2=80=99t work: Corporations need some way to return money =
to shareholders. The main options are dividends (pay cash directly to each =
shareholder and let them keep the shares) and stock buybacks (pay cash to s=
ome shareholders to buy their shares). Buybacks have some big advantages; i=
n particular, they are=C2=A0<em>flexible:=C2=A0</em>A company that has a bi=
g profit one year and no profit the next year can buy back stock the first =
year and not the second year. Dividends tend to be thought of as less flexi=
ble: A company that declares a 10-cent dividend one year is expected to kee=
p it up the next year. This is not particularly grounded in science =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0there is no reason the company=C2=A0<em>couldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em=
>cut its dividend when times get tough, and companies often, though grudgin=
gly, do =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it does seem to be the case that dividends vary =
less than buybacks.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a> So companies are more often making=C2=A0<em>affirmative decisions=C2=
=A0</em>to do buybacks, so they get more attention, and if your view is tha=
t companies should never pay money back to shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0that=
 they should just reinvest it in the business or pay higher salaries or wha=
tever =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you tend to express that by disliking buybacks.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But buybacks have another advantage over divid=
ends, from the company=E2=80=99s perspective, which is that they are tax-ef=
ficient. If you pay a dividend, in the US, every (taxable) shareholder pays=
 (<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30494731.273449/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaXJzLmdvdi9wdWJsaWNhdGlvbnMvcDU1MCNlbl9VU18yMDIxX3B1Ymxpbms=
xMDAwMTAwNzU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe81d1297" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">probably</a>=C2=A0<=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30494731.273449/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuaXJzLmdvdi90YXh0b3BpY3MvdGM0MDQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBee6ed=
231" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">capital gains</a>)=C2=A0taxes on the full amount of the divide=
nd. But if you buy back stock, then only the shareholders who sell stock pa=
y taxes: The ones who keep their stock (and presumably benefit from a highe=
r stock price and more concentrated ownership) don=E2=80=99t have any taxab=
le income. And even the ones who sell their stock only pay (capital gains) =
taxes on their=C2=A0<em>gains:=C2=A0</em>If they bought stock at $20 and so=
ld it back to the company at $30, they have only $10 of taxable income, not=
 $30. So the shareholders pay less tax on buybacks than on dividends, so sh=
areholders prefer buybacks, so companies also like buybacks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is standard corporate finance advice, but=
 from the perspective of, say, the US government, it might seem bad. Compan=
ies want to return money to shareholders, there are two roughly equivalent =
ways for them to do it, one is more traditional (dividends) and the other i=
s newer and more controversial (buybacks), and the newer and more controver=
sial=C2=A0one results in less tax revenue for the government.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you run=C2=A0the government, this is I thin=
k a perfectly sensible reason to worry about stock buybacks. If this is you=
r worry, though, you would not go around banning stock buybacks to require =
companies to invest all of their profits forever in building new factories.=
 You would just =E2=80=A6=C2=A0raise taxes on stock buybacks? I suppose you=
 could do this in some complicated way in which a buyback is deemed to trig=
ger taxable income for all shareholders, etc., such that the tax treatment =
of dividends and buybacks was exactly the same, but that seems exhausting. =
Easier to just slap an extra=C2=A0tax on buybacks, at the corporate level, =
to get some crude equivalence.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway President Joe Biden put a 1% tax on buy=
backs, and in the State of the Union address last night he <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30494731.273449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDYvYmlkZW4tdG8tY2FsbC1mb3ItY=
mlsbGlvbmFpcmUtdGF4LWJpZ2dlci1sZXZ5LW9uLXN0b2NrLWJ1eWJhY2tzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAy=
MDgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV=
0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIwOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB499af385" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">  called for raising it to 4%</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The 1% stock buyback tax that was part of Bide=
n=E2=80=99s Inflation Reduction Act went into effect at the start of this y=
ear, but it isn=E2=80=99t expected to tamp down corporations=E2=80=99 plans=
 to repurchase their own shares, because the 1% rate is too low to act as a=
 deterrent.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Democrats had hoped that increasing the cost o=
f stock buybacks would prod companies to use their cash on hand to raise wo=
rkers=E2=80=99 wages or invest in new endeavors, bolstering the economy.</p=
>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The idea that companies shouldn=E2=80=99t retu=
rn capital to shareholders still strikes me as odd, but it does seem like t=
here=E2=80=99s room to raise buyback taxes to make them more equivalent to =
dividends.</p>
